In the United States, the **Oath of Allegiance** is the official oath taken by new citizens during naturalization ceremonies. It is a formal declaration of loyalty to the U.S. and its Constitution. The full text is as follows:

> "I hereby declare, on oath, that I absolutely and entirely renounce and abjure all allegiance and fidelity to any foreign prince, potentate, state, or sovereignty, of whom or which I have heretofore been a subject or citizen;
> 
> that I will support and defend the Constitution and laws of the United States of America against all enemies, foreign and domestic;
> 
> that I will bear true faith and allegiance to the same;
> 
> that I will bear arms on behalf of the United States when required by the law;
> 
> that I will perform noncombatant service in the Armed Forces of the United States when required by the law;
> 
> that I will perform work of national importance under civilian direction when required by the law;
> 
> and that I take this obligation freely, without any mental reservation or purpose of evasion; so help me God."

**Key points:**
*   **Renunciation of Prior Allegiance:** The oath begins with renouncing loyalty to any other country.
*   **Defense of the Constitution:** It includes a promise to support and defend the U.S. Constitution.
*   **Service Obligations:** It commits the individual to various forms of service if required by law (military, noncombatant, or civilian work).
*   **Solemn Undertaking:** It is taken freely and without reservation.

**Note:** For individuals who cannot swear an oath to "bear arms" or perform certain types of service due to religious beliefs or conscientious objections, the law allows for modifications to those specific clauses. The phrase "so help me God" is also optional.
